 finds the intersection between migration and religion and calls attention to quieter voices, those dedicated to securing the human dignity of newcomers. Based on years of fieldwork conducted in California's major centers as well as in Chicago, this book considers Muslim Americans defending their civil liberties after 9/11, Christian activists responding to death and violence at the U.S-Mexico border, and Christian and Jewish clergy defending the labor rights of Latino immigrants. At a time when much attention has been given to religious fundamentalism and its capacity to incite violent conflict, God's Heart Has No Borders revises our understanding of the role of religion in social movements and demonstrates the nonviolent power of religious groups to address social injustices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFaith-based human serviceszUnited States. 0aReligion and justice. 0aReligion and statezUnited States. 0aSocial justicexReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  aamerican activism.  aamerican religions.  acalifornia.  achicago.  achristian activism.  achristian americans.  achristianity.  acivil liberties.  adeath.  ahuman dignity.  aimmigrant rights.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration and emigration.  aislam.  ajewish activism.  ajudaism.  alabor rights.  alatino immigrants.  amajor world religions.  amigration.  amuslim activism.  amuslim americans.  anonviolent protest.  apolitical.  areligion.  areligious activism.  areligious groups.  asocial injustice.  asocial movements.  aunited states of america.  aus mexican border.  aviolence.  axenophobia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025724540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525